{"source_key":"sha256-a74ceb5e1c9633ab993c14c11d587d71","record_index":5090,"record_hash":"sha256:b00f3cd5c03e4610dd5070075cd48f963a96b71ce3ccffc536c014c9b8ce4d3f","timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:48:41.012Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 827f6d\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2115\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Handoff Design\n\nThis note describes the current agent-facing read workflow on top of\n`but-agentlog`. It is design context, not a skill file and not an implementation\ncontract.\n\n## Goal\n\nLet a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\nanother machine, agent, or provider session.\n\nThe target experience:\n\n1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n5. the agent uses GitButler commands to skim prior work and drill down only when\n   needed\n6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n\nThis is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n\n## Current Surface\n\nThe current agent-facing read surface is deliberately small:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog skim\nbut agentlog skim branch <branch-name-or-ref>\nbut agentlog skim review <review-id-or-key>\nbut agentlog skim change <change-id-or-key>\nbut agentlog show <session-key> [--limit 20]\nbut agentlog show <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--limit 20]\n```\n\n`skim` is the default. It finds every session related to the target and shows\nevery turn in those sessions, in chronological order, with abbreviated user and\nassistant previews. It does not select \"important\" turns and it does not cap the\nnumber of sessions. The whole point is that the agent sees the full turn shape,\njust compactly.\n\n`show` is the drill-down command. It reads exact detail for one session or one\nturn when the skim is too thin, contradictory, or the task requires evidence.\nTurn-level `show` is bounded by default so one large backfill does not dump a\nwhole transcript.\n\nThe old `recap` idea is gone. It selected a subset of turns and risked feeling\nauthoritative while being incomplete. `skim` is b\n[TRUNCATED]\nonal human-readable output for manual debugging\n\nDo not bake a model-generated summary into storage. If a summary exists later,\nmake it a derived convenience artifact, not the source of truth.\n\n## Prior Art Notes\n\nResearch as of 2026-05-20 points to a few strong patterns.\n\n### Native Session Resume\n\n[Claude Code sessions](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/sessions) and\n[GitHub Copilot CLI session data](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/how-tos/copilot-cli/use-copilot-cli/chronicle)\nboth expose direct resume flows:\n\n- continue the most recent session\n- open a session picker\n- resume by session id or name\n- rename sessions\n- export or share a transcript\n\nThe lesson for GitButler is not to mimic native resume. Native resume only works\ninside one provider's session model. GitButler's stronger role is portable\nreference: help a different machine or agent discover, inspect, and selectively\nload prior work.\n\n### Checkpoints And Durable State\n\n[LangGraph persistence](https://langchain-5e9cc07a.mintlify.app/oss/python/langgraph/persistence)\nand\n[Copilot SDK session persistence](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/how-tos/copilot-sdk/use-copilot-sdk/session-persistence)\nseparate a stable thread/session id from resumable checkpoints or state.\n\nThe lesson is to keep agentlog turns as durable checkpoints of observed work,\nand to avoid assuming the receiving agent has the same runtime, tools, model, or\nprovider.\n\n### Resources, Tools, And Prompts\n\n[MCP server concepts](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/learn/server-concepts)\ndraws a useful line:\n\n- tools are model-invoked operations\n- resources are discoverable context\n- prompts are reusable user-controlled workflows\n\nThat maps well to the current shape:\n\n- `skim` is the compact context resource\n- `show` is the explicit read tool\n- a skill or prompt teaches when to use each one\n\nThe lesson is to make the data browseable and bounded, not to force everything\nthrough a generated summary.\n\n### Context Providers And Repo Maps\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-21T05:48:41.012Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}